00:07:16.349 --> 00:07:23.150
So let's talk a little bit more about the
terms behind advertising. So these are some

00:07:23.150 --> 00:07:27.610
basic concepts on advertising. If you are
familiar with these, don't worry. This will

00:07:27.610 --> 00:07:30.930
go by pretty quickly.
The first term we are going to talk about

00:07:30.930 --> 00:07:36.039
is cost per click or CPC. This is how much
money you get paid when a user clicks on an

00:07:36.039 --> 00:07:38.620
ad.
We are going to go through some examples so

00:07:38.620 --> 00:07:42.650
we are going to use example numbers here and
in our examples we are going to use ten cents

00:07:42.650 --> 00:07:47.629
as a cost per click. So you get paid ten cents
every time a user clicks on an ad -- or clicks

00:07:47.629 --> 00:07:53.680
on an ad in your application.
The next term is ad request. This is when

00:07:53.680 --> 00:07:59.629
your application goes out to the ad network
and says I want to show an ad. Simple as that.

00:07:59.629 --> 00:08:03.289
So in the examples we are going to use 120,000
ad requests.

00:08:03.289 --> 00:08:07.899
Now, this is different than impressions, which
is the next term. An impression is actually

00:08:07.899 --> 00:08:13.389
when an ad is shown in your application and
the user has a chance to click on it. So not

00:08:13.389 --> 00:08:18.040
every ad request results in an impression,
and I will explain that later and the terms

00:08:18.040 --> 00:08:23.599
behind that.
And in our example, as I said, 100,000 impressions.

00:08:23.599 --> 00:08:30.409
The ads were shown 100,000 times.
The fourth one on this slide is clicks. So

00:08:30.409 --> 00:08:35.061
we're going to use 1500 clicks, and clicks
are self-explanatory. That's when the user

00:08:35.061 --> 00:08:43.910
actually taps on an ad in your application.
So combining some of these terms is a more

00:08:43.910 --> 00:08:50.150
advanced term called click-through rate. This
is a good measurement for when -- a measurement

00:08:50.150 --> 00:08:55.040
of how relevant the ads are to the users.
So click-through rate is calculated by clicks

00:08:55.040 --> 00:09:01.000
divided by impressions. So in our example,
like I said, 1500 clicks divided by 100,000

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:07.750
impressions results in a 1.5% CTR. So 1.5%
of the time a user saw an ad, they liked it

00:09:07.750 --> 00:09:15.900
and clicked on it because it was helpful to
them, and so in our example, 1.5% CTR.

00:09:15.900 --> 00:09:18.560
The next term is revenue, how much money you
are making.

00:09:18.560 --> 00:09:25.620
That's calculated by the number of clicks
multiplied by the cost per click, pretty easy.

00:09:25.620 --> 00:09:32.250
1500 clicks multiplied by ten cents results
in $150 in revenue.

00:09:32.250 --> 00:09:37.270
So for these numbers, the publisher here made
$150.

00:09:37.270 --> 00:09:45.460
Now, the next term is a little bit more advanced
term, eCPM. This is effective cost per million.

00:09:45.460 --> 00:09:53.800
It's essentially, in simple terms, how much
money am I expected to make per thousand impressions.

00:09:53.800 --> 00:10:01.780
This is a common metric to gauge ad networks.
It's not the only network, but it is one of

00:10:01.780 --> 00:10:06.400
the most useful ones because there's multiple
ways you can buy advertising. In our examples

00:10:06.400 --> 00:10:11.310
we are only use CPC. It's every time someone
clicks on an ad, you get paid. There's another

00:10:11.310 --> 00:10:18.960
way to buy advertising, such as CPM. You can
get paid on an impression basis. CPA or cost

00:10:18.960 --> 00:10:22.520
per acquisition. You get paid when there is
acquisition.

00:10:22.520 --> 00:10:29.560
So eCPM is a way to measure across -- to level
the playing field and kind of have one metric

00:10:29.560 --> 00:10:34.840
to judge how much money you are going to make
off of different ad networks.

00:10:34.840 --> 00:10:40.130
So the calculation is revenue divided by a
thousand -- or divided by impressions multiplied

00:10:40.130 --> 00:10:47.210
by a thousand. So that's expected cost per
-- or expected revenue per thousand impressions.

00:10:47.210 --> 00:10:53.930
So in our example, 150 divided by 100,000
times a thousand, $1.50. So for every thousand

00:10:53.930 --> 00:11:01.030
impressions, you expect to make $1.50. Pretty
straightforward.

00:11:01.030 --> 00:11:08.510
I said earlier not every ad request results
in an impression, and that number is called

00:11:08.510 --> 00:11:16.950
fill rate. It's essentially impressions divided
by ad requests. So in this example, 100,000

00:11:16.950 --> 00:11:23.200
impressions from 120,000 ads, 83% fill rate.
Now, fill rate some people would expect to

00:11:23.200 --> 00:11:31.070
be 100 percent but there are many reasons
why an ad request doesn't result in an impression.

00:11:31.070 --> 00:11:38.970
There are things such as available ad inventory.
GO is a large one. There may not be a relevant

00:11:38.970 --> 00:11:46.030
ad to serve to someone in Finland, for example.
It's just a fact of ad networks, and not reaching

00:11:46.030 --> 00:11:51.640
100 percent fill is common and it's not something
that should be looked down upon because it's

00:11:51.640 --> 00:11:58.310
-- it shows that we want -- as an ad network
and as a developer, too, you want to show

00:11:58.310 --> 00:12:03.010
the most relevant ad to your user. And in
some cases there may not be one. Simple as

00:12:03.010 --> 00:12:07.410
that.
Let's combine all these terms I have been

00:12:07.410 --> 00:12:15.620
talking about into a more complicated scenario.
So in this scenario that's on the screen back

00:12:15.620 --> 00:12:22.120
